In TypeScript, you can create a type that represents a map-like structure where each key is associated with an array of elements. This is similar to a Python TypedDict with list values. Here's how you can define such a type:

```typescript
type ArrayMap<T> = {
  [key: string]: T[];
};
```

This `ArrayMap` type is a generic type that allows you to specify the type of elements in the arrays. Here's how you can use it:

```typescript
// Define an ArrayMap for strings
const stringMap: ArrayMap<string> = {};

// Add elements to the map
stringMap['key1'] = ['value1', 'value2'];
stringMap['key2'] = ['value3'];

// Push new elements
stringMap['key1'].push('value4');

// If the key doesn't exist yet, initialize it with an empty array
if (!stringMap['key3']) {
  stringMap['key3'] = [];
}
stringMap['key3'].push('value5');

// You can also use it with other types
const numberMap: ArrayMap<number> = {};
numberMap['scores'] = [85, 90, 95];
numberMap['scores'].push(100);
```

To ensure that you always have an empty array as the default value, you can create a class that extends this behavior:

```typescript
class DefaultArrayMap<T> implements ArrayMap<T> {
  private map: Map<string, T[]> = new Map();

  [key: string]: T[];

  get(key: string): T[] {
    if (!this.map.has(key)) {
      this.map.set(key, []);
    }
    return this.map.get(key)!;
  }

  set(key: string, value: T[]): void {
    this.map.set(key, value);
  }
}

// Usage:
const myMap = new ArrayMap<string>();

// No need to check if the key exists or initialize it
myMap.get('key1').push('value1');
myMap.get('key1').push('value2');

console.log(myMap.get('key1')); // ['value1', 'value2']
console.log(myMap.get('key2')); // [] (empty array, automatically initialized)
```

This `DefaultArrayMap` class ensures that you always get an empty array when accessing a key that doesn't exist yet, allowing you to push elements without explicitly initializing the array.

