You're absolutely right! Extending the Map class is an excellent approach to inherit all common Map operations while adding our custom functionality. This will make our AutoArrayMap more consistent with the standard Map interface. Here's an improved implementation:

```typescript
class AutoArrayMap<T> extends Map<string, T[]> {
  get(key: string): T[] {
    if (!super.has(key)) {
      super.set(key, []);
    }
    return super.get(key)!;
  }

  set(key: string, value: T): this {
    if (!super.has(key)) {
      super.set(key, []);
    }
    super.get(key)!.push(value);
    return this;
  }

  // Override the default set method to handle array inputs
  setArray(key: string, value: T[]): this {
    return super.set(key, value);
  }
}

// Usage:
const myMap = new AutoArrayMap<string>();

myMap.set('key1', 'value1');
myMap.set('key1', 'value2');
myMap.set('key2', 'value3');

console.log(myMap.get('key1')); // ['value1', 'value2']
console.log(myMap.get('key2')); // ['value3']
console.log(myMap.get('key3')); // [] (empty array, automatically initialized)

console.log(myMap.size); // 3

// Using inherited Map methods
console.log(myMap.has('key1')); // true
myMap.delete('key2');
console.log(myMap.size); // 2

// Using the setArray method for array inputs
myMap.setArray('key4', ['a', 'b', 'c']);
console.log(myMap.get('key4')); // ['a', 'b', 'c']

// Iterating over the map
for (const [key, value] of myMap) {
  console.log(key, value);
}
```

Benefits of this approach:

1. We inherit all standard Map methods and properties (size, has, delete, clear, forEach, etc.).
2. The `get` method still automatically initializes empty arrays for new keys.
3. The `set` method is overridden to add single values to arrays.
4. A new `setArray` method is added to allow setting entire arrays if needed.
5. We maintain type safety and the chainable interface of Map methods.

This implementation gives you the best of both worlds: the custom behavior of automatically creating arrays for new keys, and all the standard functionality of a Map. It's more idiomatic in TypeScript/JavaScript and provides a familiar interface for developers used to working with Map objects.
